## Indicator Variables: Introduction

We previously asserted that categorical variables, such as "shirt color", are not typically included in regression, since it is difficult to interpret a numerical coefficient for a discrete categorical series.

One common exception is using **indicator variables** which encode categorical information. A special kind of indicator variable is called a **dummy variable** which are coded as being only zero or one.

We may have a single indicator variable for a binary outcome (*male*=1 vs. *male*=0) or a set of indicator variables that span the possible options (*red shirt, blue shirt, green shirt, ...*). Indicator variables give us a powerful way to analyze differences in means and slopes for different groups within our regression.

## Simple Dummy Variable Regression

Suppose we want to estimate the average final grade in ECN102 for Econ majors and non-majors. We could define a dummy variable $ECN=1$ for Economics majors and 0 otherwise.

We then estimate $final_i=\beta_1+\alpha_1 ECN_i+u_i$:

$$\widehat{final}_i=\begin{cases}
b_1+a_1 & ECN_i =1 \\
b_1 & ECN_i=0
\end{cases}$$

Our coefficient $a_1$ on $ECN$ is then the average difference in final grade between Econ majors and non-majors. This is the simplest use of a dummy variable.

## Graph: Final Grade on ECN Major Status

$\widehat{final}_i=b_1+a_1 ECN_i$:

```{r}
#| label: fig-dummy-intercept-only
#| fig-height: 2.6
#| fig-width: 5.5
#| fig-cap: "Schematic regression lines showing the effect of a binary dummy variable on the outcome, with no continuous regressor."
#| fig-alt: "Schematic graph with Hours studying on the x-axis and Final grade on the y-axis, both unlabeled numerically, with the y-axis starting at zero. Two horizontal lines span the full x-range: a solid dark-blue line for Non-major (ECN = 0) at a lower level, and a dashed purple line for Econ major (ECN = 1) at a higher level. A double-headed vertical arrow near the y-axis labeled b1 spans from the x-axis at y equals zero up to the non-major line, showing the y-intercept. A second double-headed vertical arrow between the two lines labeled a1 shows the upward shift from the dummy variable. The graph illustrates that with only a dummy regressor the model predicts a constant grade for each group, differing only by a1 above the baseline b1."
#| warning: false
library(ggplot2)
b1 <- 30; a1 <- 10

df1 <- data.frame(
  x     = c(0, 10, 0, 10),
  y     = c(b1, b1, b1 + a1, b1 + a1),
  group = c("nm", "nm", "em", "em")
)

ggplot(df1, aes(x, y, color = group, linetype = group)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 0.9) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("nm" = "#003087", "em" = "#ac47be")) +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = c("nm" = "solid", "em" = "dashed")) +
  annotate("segment", x = 0, xend = 0, y = 1, yend = b1 - 1,
           arrow = arrow(ends = "both", length = unit(0.08, "inches")),
           color = "#333333", linewidth = 0.5) +
  annotate("text", x = 0.25, y = b1 / 2,
           label = expression(italic(b)[1]),
           color = "#333333", size = 3.2, hjust = 0) +
  annotate("segment", x = 0, xend = 0, y = b1, yend = b1 + a1,
           arrow = arrow(ends = "both", length = unit(0.05, "inches")),
           color = "#333333", linewidth = 0.5) +
  annotate("text", x = 0.25, y = b1 + a1 / 2,
           label = expression(italic(a)[1]),
           color = "#333333", size = 3.2, hjust = 0) +
  annotate("text", x = 7, y = b1 - 3.5,
           label = "Non-major (ECN = 0)", color = "#003087", size = 3.0, hjust = 0.5) +
  annotate("text", x = 7, y = b1 + a1 + 3.5,
           label = "Econ major (ECN = 1)", color = "#ac47be", size = 3.0, hjust = 0.5) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 10), ylim = c(0, 55)) +
  labs(x = "Hours studying", y = "Final grade") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = "none",
        axis.text = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank())
```

## Dummy Variables in Multivariate Regression

We may also want to include dummy variables in a multivariate regression with other continuous numerical regressors. In this case, the partial effect (estimated coefficient) of the dummy variable is the change in our outcome when our dummy goes from 0 to 1, all other regressors held constant. The total effect is our partial effect added to the product of any correlated movement in other variables and its associated coefficient.

We now estimate: $$final_i=\beta_1+\beta_2hrs_i+\alpha_1 ECN_i+u_i$$ where $hrs$ is the number of hours spent studying and $ECN=1$ is being an Econ major. Now, our estimated coefficient $a_1$ is the average difference in final grades between Econ majors and non-majors holding time spent studying fixed.

## Graph: Final Grade, Hours, and ECN Major Status

$\widehat{final}_i=b_1+b_2hrs_i+a_1 ECN_i$:

```{r}
#| label: fig-dummy-parallel
#| fig-height: 2.6
#| fig-width: 5.5
#| fig-cap: "Schematic parallel regression lines showing a binary dummy variable added to a regression with a continuous regressor."
#| fig-alt: "Schematic graph with Hours studying on the x-axis and Final grade on the y-axis, both unlabeled numerically, with the y-axis starting at zero. Two upward-sloping parallel lines: a solid dark-blue line for Non-major (ECN = 0) and a dashed purple line for Econ major (ECN = 1) above it. A double-headed vertical arrow near the y-axis labeled b1 spans from just above the x-axis to just below the y-intercept of the non-major line, with equal gaps at each end. A second double-headed vertical arrow slightly to the right labeled a1 shows the constant gap between the two parallel lines, with equal gaps at each end. A slope triangle on the non-major line shows a dotted horizontal run and a dotted vertical rise labeled b2, illustrating the shared slope of both lines."
#| warning: false
library(ggplot2)
b1 <- 30; b2 <- 2; a1 <- 10

df2 <- data.frame(
  x     = c(0, 10, 0, 10),
  y     = c(b1, b1 + b2 * 10, b1 + a1, b1 + a1 + b2 * 10),
  group = c("nm", "nm", "em", "em")
)

ggplot(df2, aes(x, y, color = group, linetype = group)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 0.9) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("nm" = "#003087", "em" = "#ac47be")) +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = c("nm" = "solid", "em" = "dashed")) +
  annotate("segment", x = 0, xend = 0, y = 1, yend = b1 - 1,
           arrow = arrow(ends = "both", length = unit(0.08, "inches")),
           color = "#333333", linewidth = 0.5) +
  annotate("text", x = 0.25, y = b1 / 2,
           label = expression(italic(b)[1]),
           color = "#333333", size = 3.2, hjust = 0) +
  annotate("segment", x = 0, xend = 0, y = b1, yend = b1 + a1,
           arrow = arrow(ends = "both", length = unit(0.05, "inches")),
           color = "#333333", linewidth = 0.5) +
  annotate("text", x = 0.25, y = b1 + a1 / 2,
           label = expression(italic(a)[1]),
           color = "#333333", size = 3.2, hjust = 0) +
  annotate("segment", x = 2.5, xend = 4.5, y = b1 + b2 * 2.5, yend = b1 + b2 * 2.5,
           linetype = "dotted", color = "#555555", linewidth = 0.4) +
  annotate("segment", x = 4.5, xend = 4.5, y = b1 + b2 * 2.5, yend = b1 + b2 * 4.5,
           linetype = "dotted", color = "#555555", linewidth = 0.5) +
  annotate("text", x = 4.9, y = b1 + b2 * 2.5 + b2,
           label = expression(italic(b)[2]),
           color = "#333333", size = 3.2, hjust = 0) +
  annotate("text", x = 7, y = b1 + b2 * 7 - 6,
           label = "Non-major (ECN = 0)", color = "#003087", size = 3.0, hjust = 0.5) +
  annotate("text", x = 7, y = b1 + a1 + b2 * 7 + 6.5,
           label = "Econ major (ECN = 1)", color = "#ac47be", size = 3.0, hjust = 0.5) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 10), ylim = c(0, 70)) +
  labs(x = "Hours studying", y = "Final grade") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = "none",
        axis.text = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank())
```

## Interacting a Dummy Variable with a Regressor

Finally, we could **interact** our dummy variable with another regressor to capture the average difference in *slopes* between one category and another. Adding to our regression of final grades, we could estimate $$final_i=\beta_1+\beta_2hrs_i+\alpha_1ECN_i+\alpha_2(ECN_i\times hrs_i)+u_i$$

Now:

- $\beta_2$ captures the change in final grade associated with 1 additional hour of studying for *non*-majors

- $\alpha_1$ captures the average difference in overall final grades between majors and non-majors

- $\beta_2+\alpha_2$ captures the change in final grade associated with 1 additional hour of studying for *majors*

## Graph: Interacted Dummy Regression

$\widehat{final}_i=b_1+b_2hrs_i+a_1ECN_i+a_2(ECN_i\times hrs_i)$:

```{r}
#| label: fig-dummy-interaction
